Content:
Alhamdulillah. Yesterday we had the honour of hosting our loved ones for Raya.

It wasnâ€™t just an ordinary visit â€” it held deep meaning for us.
29 and 27 years ago, my wifeâ€™s parents left (passed away) her and her siblings at a young age.
Since then, it was abang who stepped up â€” carrying both roles â€” always there to guide, support, and protect them like his own.

Being able to welcome him and his family into our home this Raya brought a different kind of warmth.
Seeing the kids â€” the cucus â€” laughing, playing, and bonding so naturally made us feel as if Ayah and Ibu were with us too, smiling over the gathering.

Moments like these remind me â€” itâ€™s not about how grand the house is or how lavish the spread.
Itâ€™s about the barakah in the hearts that fill the space.

Alhamdulillah for blessings that words sometimes cannot even describe.

Name: WEE LI TING
Content:
[13 April 2025 | Bali, Indonesia]

This year, I made a spontaneous decision by booking a solo trip to Bali for my birthday. Behind the spontaneity was a quiet need for something more - more clarity, more courage, more connection with myself. The thought of being alone in an unfamiliar place can be intimidating. But thereâ€™s no one to distract me, from me. And in that silence, I started to listen. I listened moreâ€”to the world around me and to myself. I noticed the little things: the art that spoke to me, dogs chasing waves, the sound of the ocean crashing onto shore. I confronted thoughts and feelings I usually drowned out with busyness. I learnt to appreciate my own pace, my own rhythm. I celebrated myself for the first time and celebrated with strangers who I may never meet again. And in all of that, I found a deep fulfilling sense of freedom ğŸ«¶ğŸ»

Name: CHENG LI CHIANG STEVE
Content:
Part 2
Disclaimer: not trying to be disrespectful to anyone. Pardon the AI effect. 

â€œSir, I just want to shake your hand.â€
(He gave me a weird stareâ€¦ and a gentle smack on the arm.)

After listening to the legendary Tony Gordonâ€”the GOAT of the insurance industryâ€”share his story, I was deeply inspired.

At 79, he flew from the US to Malaysia just to spend an hour with us. He couldâ€™ve stayed in the comfort of home, or travelled with friends. But he chose to be hereâ€”to give, to serve, to lift others. That alone taught me something: greatness doesnâ€™t retire.

After his session, everyone rushed to take photos. I couldnâ€™t get close, so I cheekily â€œphoto bombedâ€ and AI-ed myself closer in Photo 1.

But eventually, as the room cleared, we got a proper photo with him.

Then came my moment.
I walked up, extended my hand, and said:
â€œSir, I just want to shake your hand.â€

He looked at me with a confused stareâ€¦ then gave me a light smack on the arm.

I wasnâ€™t trying to be cheeky or disrespectful.
I just wanted to feel the warmth of his hand.
To remind myselfâ€”heâ€™s human. Just like us.
Same warmth. Same heart. Same opportunity to do something great with our lives.

Iâ€™m grateful for this journey.
Grateful for the team and family weâ€™ve built at PFG.
And grateful even for the tough daysâ€”because theyâ€™re shaping us for something greater.

Letâ€™s keep going.
Because if he can, we can.
If he did, so can we.

A good reminder to self. - Part 2

Name: JARED THAM JIA LE
Content:
3 ğ‘¨ğ’…ğ’—ğ’‚ğ’ğ’•ğ’‚ğ’ˆğ’†ğ’” ğ’ğ’‡ ğ‘©ğ’–ğ’šğ’Šğ’ğ’ˆ ğ‘°ğ’ğ’”ğ’–ğ’“ğ’‚ğ’ğ’„ğ’† ğ‘¬ğ’‚ğ’“ğ’ğ’š (ğ’•ğ’‰ğ’‚ğ’• ğ’ğ’ğ’”ğ’• ğ’‘ğ’†ğ’ğ’‘ğ’ğ’† ğ’…ğ’ğ’'ğ’• ğ’Œğ’ğ’ğ’˜ ğ’‚ğ’ƒğ’ğ’–ğ’•) 

So, you're a young adult, right? 

It's great to be young and carefree, but as you start to take on more responsibilities and make your way in the world, some areas that we usually overlook is our physical and financial health. 

While Iâ€™m not a health coach or fitness trainer that can provide you the expertiseâ€¦

I can help with the insurance portion ;P
 
It's not the most exciting topicâ€¦ but something you really can't afford to ignore. 

So, if you're ready to learn more about why insurance is important for young adults like you, dive into this post and explore the benefits of getting covered when you're young.

âœ…Cheaper Premiums When Younger
Did you know that you can lock in your premiums at cheaper prices? 

Life insurance premiums are based on several factors, including a person's health and age. Generally, the amount you pay to purchase a life insurance policy rises as you age. 

Rates can jump considerably if you wait until you are in your mid-thirties or forties due to the higher probability that the insurer will have to make a pay out on the policy you purchased. 

âœ…Guarantee your Insurability 
Many people think they can buy insurance with moneyâ€¦.

Sorry to burst your bubble but unfortunately that isn't the case. 

You buy insurance primarily with your health. 

Almost ALL insurance policies have exemptions for pre-existing conditions, which means if you have a medical 
issue now, and buy insurance later, you won't be covered for that condition. 

The inevitable fact is that our health deteriorates as we age. Buying insurance when you're young and healthy lessens the need for medical check ups or more underwriting. We hope to be healthy forever but what if you and I are both wrong? Will it be too late?

âœ…Financial security in your Prime years ensures that you can focus on recuperating, even if it takes several years, without having to worry about paying for basic needs or family responsibilities.

And after almost 5 years in the industry, I can safely say, you will never be able to put a put a price tag on peace of mind

Name: HAN YUN JIA, JOSH
MAGESWARAN S/O DEVADAS
Content:
Why Every Sales Professional Needs Systems

In the fast-paced world of sales, success does not come by chance. It comes by design. And one of the most powerful tools a salesperson can have is a system.

When we talk about systems in sales, we are referring to a structured approach. A repeatable, reliable process that guides how we find leads, nurture relationships, present solutions and close deals. It is about turning daily chaos into a well-oiled machine.

Why does this matter?

Because systems drive productivity. They save time, reduce stress and eliminate guesswork. They help us prioritize the right clients, follow up at the right time and track the right metrics. With systems in place, we do not just work harder. We work smarter.

Imagine knowing exactly what your next step is with every prospect. Imagine having automated follow-ups that go out like clockwork. Imagine being able to train new team members with ease because everything is already mapped out.

That is the power of systems
They bring consistency
They create scalability
And most importantly, they deliver results

Sales is not just an art. It is a science. And systems are what turn potential into performance.

If you are in sales and want to rise above the noise, build your systems
